<DOC><DOCNO> AP880708-0078 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0755EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-U.N.-Environment     07-08 0289</FIRST><SECOND>PM-U.N.-Environment,0296</SECOND><HEAD>U.N. Leaders Gathering In Oslo To Discuss Environment</HEAD><BYLINE>By ERIK A. WOLD</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez deCuellar arrived in Norway today to head a high-level meeting on howthe United Nations can respond to environmental threats withoutstunting world development.   The heads of 25 specialized U.N. agencies and economiccommissions are to meet Saturday and Sunday at a closed-doorsession called by Norway's Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland.Mrs. Brundtland headed the U.N.-sponsored World Commission onEnvironment and Development and drafted a landmark report called``Our Common Future.''   ``The intention of this meeting is to get the U.N. system togive higher priority to environmental issues,'' said MortenWetland, a special advisor to Mrs. Brundtland on foreign andenvironmental affairs.   Among the issues to be raised at the conference aredeforestation, land degradation and desertification, acidification,loss of biological diversity, and air and water pollution.   Also scheduled to attend are the head of the World Bank, BarberB. Conable Jr.; Michel Camdessus, chairman of the InternationalMonetary Fund; and the heads of the World Health Organization, theInternational Atomic Energy Commission, the U.N.Educational,Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) and the U.N.Children's Fund (UNICEF).   The conference was being held amid growing awareness ofpotential environmental disasters, from the depletion of theatmosphere's ozone layer protecting the earth from harmfulradiation, to the gradual warming of the earth due to theentrapment of gases, the so-called ``greenhouse effect.''   ``Everybody is conscious of the importance of the environment,''Perez de Cuellar said Thursday on a stopover in Stockholm, Sweden.   Perez de Cuellar was meeting privately in Oslo today with Mrs.Brundtland, Foreign Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg and King Olav V.</TEXT></DOC>